How to Finance Green Transition
New York—This week in New York, world leaders gathered at the United Nations to assess the global war on climate change and submit new emissions commitments.
The climate crisis is a major issue, and our pace of action is far from enough.
We are slow to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires cooperation and efforts from the public and private sectors alike.
Luckily, thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector cooperation on curbing climate change is becoming more frequent.
Under the leadership of UN Climate Action Special Envoy Michael Bloomberg, CFLI was established with the mission of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled Financing the Low Carbon Future, which outlines how to expand green finance to support orderly low-carbon economic transition and proposes private-public cooperation opportunities to achieve the 2015 Paris Agreement targets.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the world's largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects.
However, in response to the call of the heads of state and government of the European Union and the newly elected President of the European Commission, von der Leyen, we are now ready to take on even greater ambition and strengthen the role of EIB as the EU's specialized climate bank.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations and target low-carbon investments, with at least one trillion euros invested in low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, at least 50% of EIB financing will be used for climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will rationalize all our lending activities to be in line with the objectives of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
Furthermore, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing additional resources and helping economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As a bank of the European Union, our task is to invest in the future of Europe, and the most important issue is climate change.
The urgency of the climate crisis is reflected in the strength of our resolve.
This summer, European countries have suffered a record high temperature and crop failure due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena have been costing dozens of billions of dollars in damages to major cities every year, threatening the lives of even more people.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, because financing new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce the air pollution that plagues the world's major cities.
Changing investment patterns can accelerate a transition away from fossil fuels. This transition is already underway.
Market forces are increasingly turning to clean energy, moving away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, half of the U.S. coal-fired power plants retired, while the clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 in the coal industry.
Furthermore, more and more U.S. cities and states are committing to achieve net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from Beyond Carbon, a plan launched by the Bloomberg Foundation last year to support the full decarbonization of the US economy.
As international society, we not only need to invest in clean energy, we need to reduce our investment in dirty energy.
Currently, when looking at fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially still spending to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investment towards electric vehicles and other paradigm-shifting technologies that can drive green transformation.
These investments will yield huge returns, including the huge cost savings for public health due to reduced air pollution.
Except for this, we can also take numerous measures to guide the necessary funds.
Firstly, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, companies and investors were unaware of the climate-related risks, not knowing the rationality of reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from the impacts of extreme weather.
This is now changing.
The Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures is guiding companies to configure capital in a more sustainable way, and allowing investors to reward companies that seriously tackle climate change.
Secondly, we must clarify the investment risks related to green finance.
Cities contributed more than 70% of CO2 emissions, but only a few developing world cities were able to get credit ratings.
As a result, total investment in clean buses, energy-efficient buildings and other emissions-reducing projects was affected.
Governments and listed banks need to step up their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including taking the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by EIB and co-led with Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Thirdly, we need to modernize the grid.
Refunds and tax incentives such as these have promoted the expansion of wind power and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar plans to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies to overcome intermittent issues.
Additionally, better grid connectivity can allow surplus wind and solar power areas to supply areas in demand.
The government can take the lead in these two areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
